**Steps to Reproduce**:

1. Create the following csproj file, named *Meta.csproj*. The msbuild locator section in my case was copied from [here](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/visualstudio/msbuild/updating-an-existing-application?view=vs-2019#use-microsoftbuildlocator), however, I had to up the version from 15.1.548 to 15.3.409, since this is the minimum version `Microsoft.CodeAnalysis` of version 3.9.0 supports, I think.
```xml
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
  
    <PropertyGroup>
        <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>
        <TargetFramework>net4.8</TargetFramework>
        <RootNamespace>Meta</RootNamespace>
        <StartupObject>Meta.Program</StartupObject>
    </PropertyGroup>

    <ItemGroup>
        <!-- Prevents copying msbuild dlls into the output directory. Instead, locate the ones on system -->
        <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Build" Version="15.3.409" ExcludeAssets="runtime" />
        <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Build.Utilities.Core" Version="15.3.409" ExcludeAssets="runtime" />
        <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Build.Locator" Version="1.1.2"/>
    </ItemGroup>

    <ItemGroup>
        <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.CodeAnalysis" Version="3.9.0" />
        <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.Workspaces.Common" Version="3.9.0" />
        <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.Workspaces.MSBuild" Version="3.9.0" />
    </ItemGroup>

</Project>
```
2. Create 2 files: *Code.cs* and *Main.cs* with the following contents:
```c#
// Code.cs
namespace Code
{
    interface Hello{}
    class World : Hello{}
}
```
```c#
// Main.cs
using System;
using System.Linq;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using Microsoft.Build.Locator;
using Microsoft.CodeAnalysis;
using Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.FindSymbols;
using Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.MSBuild;

namespace Meta
{
    class Program
    {
        public static Task Main()
        {
            MSBuildLocator.RegisterDefaults();
            return Test3();
        }

        public static async Task Test3()
        {
            var msWorkspace = MSBuildWorkspace.Create();

            var solution = msWorkspace.CurrentSolution;
            solution.Workspace.WorkspaceFailed += (s, args) => Console.WriteLine(args.Diagnostic.Message);
            solution.Workspace.WorkspaceChanged += (s, args) => Console.WriteLine(args.ProjectId);

            var project = await msWorkspace.OpenProjectAsync("Meta.csproj");
            var compilation = await project.GetCompilationAsync();
            var hello = (INamedTypeSymbol)compilation.GetSymbolsWithName("Hello").Single();
            var world = (INamedTypeSymbol)compilation.GetSymbolsWithName("World").Single();

            if (!SymbolEqualityComparer.Default.Equals(world.Interfaces.Single(), hello))
            {
                Console.WriteLine("Nope 1"); return;
            }

            var implementations = await SymbolFinder.FindImplementationsAsync(hello, solution);

            if (!SymbolEqualityComparer.Default.Equals(implementations.Single(), world))
            {
                Console.WriteLine("Nope 2"); return;
            }
        }
    }
}
```
3. Run the code through `dotnet run`. You may also run it in Visual Studio, however then you'd have to adjust the path to the project accordingly.

**Expected Behavior**:

`SymbolFinder.FindImplementationsAsync()` returns a collection with 1 element — the symbol for the `World` class.

**Actual Behavior**:

`SymbolFinder.FindImplementationsAsync()` returns a collection with no elements and the program crashes (because `.Single()` is used).


**Remarks**:

This might as well not be a bug, but just me misunderstanding the API. This may also be related to my setup.

The workspace loads without errors. I can see the dll's referenced by the project by looping through the metadata list.

Lines ` var hello = (INamedTypeSymbol)compilation.GetSymbolsWithName("Hello").Single();` and `var world = (INamedTypeSymbol)compilation.GetSymbolsWithName("World").Single();` are able to retrieve the symbols.

Other methods of `SymbolFinder` also work incorrectly.

I have not tried creating an actual solution and loading that instead of just a single project file, but I do not expect that to solve the issue.

